e, Iver, Knud.","Norwegian, Danish, and North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Erik</i>, from Old Norse <i>Eiríkr</i> (see   Erickson  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ericksen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Alf, Eyvind, Astrid, Bent, Lars, Lief, Nels, Nils, Sig.","Americanized form (and a very rare Norwegian and Danish variant) of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Eriksen   or   Erichsen  . Compare   Erickson  ."]},{"name":"Errickson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Eriksen  ,   Erikson  , etc."]},{"name":"Erickson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Nels, Thor, Nils, Lars, Sven, Lief, Anders, Lennart, Iver, Elof, Erland.","Americanized form (and a rare Swedish variant) of Swedish   Ericsson   and   Eriksson  , Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Eriksen   and   Erichsen  , or of any other Scandinavian or North German patronymic from a personal name derived from Old Norse <i>Eiríkr</i>, which is composed of <i>ei</i> ‘ever, always’ (or a shortened form of <i>ein</i> ‘one, only’) + <i>rík</i> ‘power’. Compare   Ericksen  ,   Ericson  , and   Erikson  .","English (Lancashire): patronymic from the Middle English male personal name <i>Eric</i> (with the same etymology as 1 above) + <i>son</i>."]}]},{"name":"Harald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old Norse personal name <i>Haraldr</i>, meaning ‘army leader’, cognate with English <b>Harold</b>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"'Kesja'","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A female name; perhaps the same name a Keziah."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1353271,"age":11,"year":"1028","julianDay":2096529,"description":"King Canute is declared ruler of Denmark, England and Norway.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1353272,"age":43,"year":"1060","julianDay":2108217,"description":"Svend II forms Danish church.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Harald 'Kesja